THESE PATIENTS CAN BE OF ANY AGE, RACE, OR ETHNICITY, BUT THE DATA ANALYSIS INDICATES THAT RESIDENTS LIVING IN THIS SERVICE AREA ARE TRADITIONALLY OLDER, SICKER, AND POORER.   THE CATCH NETWORK WAS FORMED IN 1994. IT HAS A LONG HISTORY OF SUCCESSFUL COLLABORATION BETWEEN LHDS AND PRIMARY CARE CLINICS AND STRIVES TO PROMOTE COMMUNITY HEALTH AND DEVELOPMENT BY CONNECTING PEOPLE, IDEAS, AND RESOURCES. THERE ARE CURRENTLY 26 MEMBERS: SIX LOCAL HEALTH DEPARTMENTS (LHDS), TEN HOSPITAL SYSTEMS, EIGHT CLINICS, ONE FEDERALLY QUALIFIED HEALTH CARE CLINIC, AND ONE COMMUNITY ACTION AGENCY. FOR THIS PROJECT, FOUR LHDS AND FOUR RURAL HEALTH CLINICS WILL BE INVOLVED IN THE IMPLEMENTATION ACTIVITIES.    ACTIVITIES WILL BE FOCUSED ON IMPROVING THE CAPACITY TO DELIVER BEHAVIORAL HEALTH SERVICES AND ADDRESSING SOCIAL NEEDS. ONE ACTIVITY IS TO IDENTIFY BEHAVIORAL HEALTH PRACTITIONERS AN D DEVELOP A FRAMEWORK FOR INTEGRATING BEHAVIORAL HEALTH SERVICES WITH PRIMARY CARE AND PUBLIC HEALTH. IT ALSO INCLUDES USING A SCREENING TOOL TO IDENTIFY PATIENTS WITH PHYSICAL, MENTAL, LIFESTYLE RISK BEHAVIORS, AND SOCIAL NEEDS. ONCE THESE NEEDS ARE IDENTIFIED, A TREATMENT AND PREVENTION PLAN WILL BE DEVELOPED BY THE LOCAL COMPREHENSIVE HEALTH CARE TEAM, INCLUDING PUBLIC HEALTH PROFESSIONALS, WHO HAVE EXPERTISE IN ADDRESSING THE DIMENSIONS OF LIFESTYLE BEHAVIORS AND SOCIAL NEEDS OF THESE PATIENTS. THESE PATIENTS WILL BE REFERRED TO LOCAL PUBLIC HEALTH AGENCIES WHO WILL EDUCATE THEM ON HOW TO PREVENT AND CONTROL CHRONIC DISEASES AND/OR CONNECT THEM TO THE APPROPRIATE COMMUNITY-BASED ORGANIZATIONS TO ADDRESS THEIR SOCIAL DETERMINANT NEEDS.   THE EXPECTED OUTCOMES OF THIS PROJECT ARE TO IMPROVE INDIVIDUAL AND POPULATION HEALTH OUTCOMES (III), REDUCE THE BARRIERS THAT LIMIT ACCESS TO CARE (I), DECREASE HEALTH CARE COSTS THROUGH A REDUCTION IN EMERGENCY DEPARTMENT VISITS AND AVOIDABLE HOSPITALIZATIONS (III), INTEGRATE BEHAVIORAL HEALTH SERVICES WITH PRIMARY CARE CLINICS AND LOCAL PUBLIC HEALTH DEPARTMENTS (II), AND STRENGTHEN COMMUNITY PROGRAMS BY REFERRING HIGH-RISK PATIENTS TO PREVENTIVE PROGRAMS AND ACTIVITIES PROVIDED BY COMMUNITY ORGANIZATIONS (IV). THROUGH ENHANCED CARE COORDINATION OF PATIENTS WITH BEHAVIORAL HEALTH AND SOCIAL NEEDS, THERE WILL BE A POSITIVE IMPACT ON HEALTH OUTCOMES AND THE NETWORK WILL BECOME MORE SUSTAINABLE.   THE CATCH NETWORK IS REQUESTING A FUNDING PREFERENCE DESIGNATION BASED ON QUALIFICATION 1, HEALTH PROFESSIONAL SHORTAGE AREA. OF THE 21 COUNTIES IN THE PROJECT SERVICE AREA, 17 HAVE HPSA DESIGNATION AND 17 HAVE MUA DESIGNATION, WITH 13 COUNTIES HAVING BOTH DESIGNATIONS.

RURAL HEALTH NETWORK DEVELOPMENT PROGRAM - APPLICANT ORGANIZATION: COAL COUNTRY COMMUNITY HEALTH CENTER;  ADDRESS: 1312 HIGHWAY 49 N, BEULAH, ND 58523; TYPE: FQHC    WEBSITE: HTTPS://WWW.COALCOUNTRYHEALTH.COM/      PROJECT DIRECTOR/NETWORK DIRECTOR/KEY STAFF: DARROLD BERTSCH, NETWORK DIRECTOR: (701) 880-1140; DBERTSCH@SMCND.ORG;  DOVIE BORTH, PROJECT DIRECTOR: (701) 301-0853; DBORTH@COALCOUNTRYHEALTH.COM   PROJECT TITLE AND GOAL: THE ENERGY CAPITAL HEALTH NETWORK’S (ECHN) GOAL IS TO WORK TOGETHER TO ACHIEVE OPTIMAL COMMUNITY HEALTH AND BUILD HEALTHY COMMUNITIES THROUGH COLLABORATION AND INNOVATION.   FOCUS AREAS: WORKFORCE RECRUITMENT AND RETENTION; TECHNOLOGY ADVANCEMENTS; SERVICE DELIVERY; AND POPULATION HEALTH IMPROVEMENT.    TARGET POPULATION: THE SERVICE AREA INCLUDES DUNN, MERCER, AND OLIVER COUNTIES, AND THE SOUTHEAST PORTION OF MCKENZIE COUNTY IN NORTH DAKOTA. ALL PERSONS IN THE SERVICE AREA ARE TARGETED FOR CARE, BUT SUBPOPULATIONS INCLUDE CHILDREN AND YOUTH, THE ELDERLY, AND AMERICAN INDIANS.  NETWORK NAME AND MEMBERS: ENERGY CAPITAL HEALTH NETWORK; (1) COAL COUNTRY COMMUNITY HEALTH CENTER (CCCHC) – FQHC; (2) SAKAKAWEA MEDICAL CENTER – CRITICAL ACCESS HOSPITAL; (3) KNIFE RIVER CARE CENTER – SKILLED NURSING FACILITY; AND (4) CUSTER HEALTH – LOCAL HEALTH DEPARTMENT  PROJECT ACTIVITIES/SERVICES: (1) RECRUITMENT AND RETENTION OF STAFF. (2) TECHNOLOGY ADVANCEMENTS INCLUDING REMOTE PATIENT MONITORING, A TELEHEALTH NETWORK, AND A UNIFIED ELECTRONIC HEALTH RECORD. (3) SOCIAL DETERMINANTS OF HEALTH SCREENING; IMPROVED OBSTETRICAL OUTCOMES; AND DEVELOPMENT OF A COMMUNITY HEALTH WORKER PROGRAM. (4) EXPAND PARTNERSHIPS, IMPLEMENT A MARKETING/BRANDING CAMPAIGN, AND FACILITATE A POPULATION HEALTH COMMITTEE.       EXPECT OUTCOMES: THE OVERARCHING PROGRAM OUTCOME IS TO ACHIEVE THE QUINTUPLE AIM OF IMPROVING HEALTH OUTCOMES, DECREASING OVERALL COSTS OF CARE, IMPROVING PATIENT SATISFACTION, ADVANCING HEALTH EQUITY, AND IMPROVING CARE TEAM SATISFACTION. THAT OUTCOME ADDRESSES ALL FOUR RHND DOMAIN S. OTHER PROJECT OUTCOMES INCLUDE:   RHND DOMAIN: (I) IMPROVE ACCESS; OUTCOMES: IMPROVED EMPLOYEE SATISFACTION SCORES (STAFF RETENTION); INCREASE IN PATIENTS WITH A MEDICAL HOME.  RHND DOMAIN (II) EXPAND CAPACITY AND SERVICES; OUTCOMES: UNIFIED COMMUNICATION SYSTEM AND EHR AMONG NETWORK MEMBERS; IMPROVED CONTINUITY OF CARE; EXPANSION OF SERVICES; IMPROVED WORKFLOWS; IMPROVED COMMUNITY AWARENESS;   RHND DOMAIN (III) ENHANCE OUTCOMES; OUTCOMES: DECREASED HOSPITAL AND ER VISITS; IMPROVED POPULATION HEALTH  RHND DOMAIN: (IV) SUSTAINABILITY; OUTCOMES: NETWORK LEADERSHIP TRANSITION FINALIZED; NETWORK SUSTAINABILITY  CAPACITY TO SERVE RURAL UNDERSERVED POPULATIONS: CCCHC IS A NON-PROFIT RURAL COMMUNITY HEALTH CENTER ORGANIZATION WHICH HAS SERVED WEST CENTRAL NORTH DAKOTA FOR NEARLY 20 YEARS. ECHN PARTNERS HAVE WORKED INFORMALLY TOGETHER FOR YEARS TO ACHIEVE EFFICIENCIES IN HEALTH CARE SERVICE DELIVERY, EXPAND ACCESS TO CARE, IMPROVE QUALITY OF CARE, AND STRENGTHEN THE RURAL HEALTH DELIVERY SYSTEM. ON BEHALF OF THE ECHN, CCCHC APPLIED FOR, AND RECEIVED, A RHND PLANNING GRANT IN 2019. THE PROJECT WAS SUCCESSFULLY COMPLETED, AND THE ECHN IS WORKING TO ACHIEVE THE STRATEGIC PLANNING GOALS THAT EMERGED FROM THE GRANT. PREVIOUS COLLABORATIONS AMONG NETWORK MEMBERS WHICH DEMONSTRATE THE CAPACITY TO WORK TOGETHER INCLUDE: (1) COMPLETION OF A SERVICE AREA COMMUNITY HEALTH NEEDS ASSESSMENT; (2) SHARED FACILITY SPACE AND STAFF POSITIONS; (3) DEVELOPMENT OF THE ENERGY CAPITAL CHILDCARE COOPERATIVE; AND (4) DEVELOPMENT OF A WELLNESS CENTER.   FUNDING PREFERENCE: PREFERENCE REQUESTED BASED ON THE FOLLOWING CRITERIA: DUNN, MCKENZIE, MERCER, AND OLIVER COUNTIES ARE ALL DESIGNATED AS HEALTH PROFESSIONAL SHORTAGE AREAS. CCCHC IS ALSO LOCATED IN A MEDICALLY UNDERSERVED AREA AND SERVES A MEDICALLY UNDERSERVED POPULATION.

RURAL HEALTH NETWORK DEVELOPMENT PROGRAM - ORGANIZATION INFORMATION: CENTRACARE, 1406 6TH AVE. N., ST. CLOUD, MINNESOTA 56303-1900; WEBSITE: WWW.CENTRACARE.COM/LOCATIONS/CENTRACARE-MATERNAL-FETAL-MEDICINE/; PROJECT DIRECTOR: DAVID F. WALZ, MBA, BSN, RN, CNN, FACHE | SENIOR DIRECTOR, WOMEN’S & NEWBORN HEALTH; PHONE: 320-493-5648; WALZDAVID@CENTRACARE.COM; NETWORK DIRECTOR: SARA MUELLNER, BSN, RN, RNC-OB, 320-656-7024. FOCUS AREA: PRIMARY CARE/MATERNAL FETAL MEDICINE. PROJECT TITLE: PERINATAL OUTREACH AND RURAL TELEMEDICINE (PORT) PROJECT; FUNDS REQUESTED: $300,000 IN YEAR 1, $300,000 IN YEAR 2; 300,000 IN YEAR 3; AND, 300,000 IN YEAR 4. THE PERINATAL OUTREACH AND RURAL TELEMEDICINE (PORT) PROJECT PROVIDES PERINATAL CARE SPECIALIST SERVICES AT THREE RURAL PRIMARY CARE HEALTH CLINICS IN CENTRAL MINNESOTA, EXPANDING ACCESS TO PERINATAL CARE FOR AN ADDITIONAL 1,872 PATIENTS ANNUALLY WITH HIGH RISK PREGNANCIES WHO REQUIRE THESE SERVICES AND WHO WOULD NOT OTHERWISE HAVE ACCESS TO THESE SERVICES. THE APPLICANT ORGANIZATION IS CENTRACARE'S (CC) MATERNAL-FETAL MEDICINE (MFM) UNIT. CC IS ONE OF THE LARGEST HEALTH CARE SYSTEMS IN MINNESOTA AND INCLUDES HOSPITALS AND CLINICS TO SERVE THE HEALTH CARE NEEDS OF A RURAL, LOW-INCOME POPULATION. THE TARGET SERVICE AREA CONSISTS OF THREE RURAL COMMUNITIES THAT INCLUDE THE CITY OF MELROSE WITH A POPULATION OF 3,650 AND THE CITY OF PAYNESVILLE WITH A POPULATION OF 2,388 IN RURAL PORTIONS OF STEARNS COUNTY OUTSIDE OF ST. CLOUD, MINNESOTA’S METROPOLITAN AREA; AND, THE CITY OF WADENA WITH A POPULATION OF 4,325 IN WADENA COUNTY. EACH SITE IS HEALTH PROFESSIONAL SHORTAGE AREAS (HPSA) FOR PRIMARY CARE HPSA, DENTAL HEALTH AND MENTAL HEALTH. MELROSE IS IN A MEDICALLY UNDERSERVED AREA. ALL SITES ARE RURAL PER HRSA’S ELIGIBILITY ANALYZER. NETWORK PARTNERS ARE THE FOLLOWING: RURAL PRIMARY CLINIC SITES CC-MELROSE, CC-PAYNESVILLE AND TRI-COUNTY HEALTH CARE-WADENA CLINIC.  EACH RURAL SITE WILL RECEIVE TELE-MFM SERVICES AT THESE PRIMARY CARE PROVIDER SITES. NONE OF  THESE SITES HAVE ACCESS TO ON-SITE PERINATAL CARE. PATIENTS MUST TRAVEL TO CC-ST. CLOUD HOSPITAL MFM UNIT OR TO OTHER PERINATOLOGISTS IN MINNESOTA TO RECEIVE CARE FOLLOWING A LEVEL 1 SONOGRAM THAT INDICATES AN ISSUE WITH THE MOTHER OR FETUS AT A PRIMARY CARE APPOINTMENT OR AFTER SEEING AN OBGYN. NETWORK SERVICES AND ACTIVITIES FOR THE PORT PROJECT INCLUDE: ESTABLISH PERINATOLOGY TELEHEALTH AT THREE RURAL SITES TO INCREASE ACCESS TO PERINATOLOGY SERVICES; PROVIDE HOME HEALTH MONITORING FOR HIGH-RISK PREGNANCIES; IMPLEMENT A TEAM-BASED APPROACH FOR PERINATOLOGY; AND, PROVIDE GENETIC COUNSELING REFERRALS FOR CURRENT AND FUTURE PREGNANCIES; INCREASED REFERRALS TO PRIMARY CARE FOR COMORBIDITIES SUCH AS HYPERTENSION, CARDIOVASCULAR AND DIABETES. PROJECTED OUTCOMES INCLUDE: 1,872 PREGNANT WOMEN PER YEAR ACCESS PORT PROJECT SERVICES; MINIMUM OF 25 PREGNANT WOMEN PER YEAR ACCESS HOME HEALTH MONITORING; 100% OF PORT PATIENT HAVE TEAM-BASED CARE ACCESS; 60% OF PATIENTS RECEIVE GENETIC COUNSELING; AND, A MINIMUM OF 100 PATIENTS RECEIVE PRIMARY CARE SERVICES ANNUALLY WHO HAVE NOT PREVIOUSLY USED THESE SERVICES. CLINICAL SERVICES INCLUDE TELEHEALTH MATERNAL-FETAL CLINICAL EVALUATIONS, TREATMENT AND MATERNAL-FETAL MONITORING WILL SERVE ARE A PROJECTED 1,872 PREGNANT WOMEN EACH YEAR OF THE PROJECT PERIOD WHO CURRENTLY DO NOT HAVE ACCESS TO THESE SERVICES AT THREE PROVIDER SITES IN RURAL CENTRAL MINNESOTA. A MINIMUM OF 1,000 ULTRASOUND SCANS PER YEAR; MFM MONITORING OF 25 PATIENTS PER YEAR; ALL PATIENTS RECEIVE TEAM ACCESS AND ARE REFERRED FOR GENETIC COUNSELING. PORT IS SUSTAINABLE AS SERVICES ARE BILLED AND COSTS ARE REDUCED DUE TO NON-DUPLICATION OF SERVICES FROM LEVEL 1 TO LEVEL 2 ULTRASOUNDS. CC'S BEHAVIORAL HEALTH IMPLEMENTED A HRSA EBTBHNP GRANT AND SHARED ITS EXPERIENCE WITH THE PORT TEAM. PORT DOES NOT DUPLICATE THESE SERVICES AS ITS FOCUS IS ON MFM SERVICES. THE APPLICANT IS ELIGIBLE FOR A FUNDING PREFERENCE UNDER 42 U.S.C. 254C(H)(3)), QUALIFICATION 1 AS ALL RURAL N ETWORK SITES ARE HPSAS.
